# latin-to-maya.sdd

Scope: first conversion contract from Latin input text to Maya visual output.

## Must

- Treat Latin as input encoding, not the visual design target.
- Define a small first proof mapping before any broad alphabet work.
- Record whether each mapping is character-based, digraph-based, syllable-like, word-like, or arbitrary prototype mapping.
- Keep output glyph/sign names separate from Latin glyph names.
- Produce visual proof output that can be inspected against Maya reference material.
- Preserve a deterministic mapping table so the same Latin input gives the same Maya output.

## Must not

- Call generic Latin letter drawings a Maya design pass.
- Expand to full A-Z before the first proof mapping is approved.
- Mix recovered hieroglyph assets into Latin output silently.
- Pretend the mapping is historically/linguistically authentic unless that has been researched and approved.
- Let `adhesion`, `n/o`, or any Latin proof word become the product definition.

## Owns

- First Latin input token inventory.
- First Maya output sign/glyph inventory.
- Mapping table semantics.
- Proof strings for conversion demos.
- Gate between render-smoke and Maya-design approval.

## Depends on

- `../project-charter.md`
- `../design-principles.sdd`
- `../docs/maya-visual-north-star.md`
- recovered Maya reference material under `../recovered/source-snapshot/`

## Forbids

- Treating Latin readability as sufficient visual approval.
- Adding more Latin lowercase outline work without mapping justification.
- Shipping a binary font that only contains ordinary Latin glyphs under the Maya name.

## Done when

- A tiny Latin input set is mapped to named Maya output signs/sequences.
- The converted proof output is rendered.
- Visual inspection confirms the output reads as Maya-project output, not generic Latin.
- Elias can approve or reject the conversion direction from the proof image.
